    <node id="Gaussian Distribution">
      <data key="d0">Gaussian Distribution</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Gaussian distribution, also known as the normal distribution, is a continuous probability distribution characterized by its bell-shaped curve.&lt;SEP&gt;The Gaussian distribution, also known as the normal distribution, is a key statistical concept discussed in the lecture with applications in probability.&lt;SEP&gt;The Gaussian Distribution, also known as the normal distribution, is a continuous probability distribution characterized by its bell-shaped curve and defined by its mean and standard deviation.&lt;SEP&gt;The Gaussian distribution is a statistical distribution that is often used in different models and is recognized for its simplicity.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1dcfa4fdc2012c4e3a3c336e39e4afec&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38d7cccd02d2282bbd339ef51ba43f85&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-486f08627d119b0879789e4cf88e8904&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-023cc775f8b1adeebc9c45d2e9f6fe90</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1767701765</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Exponential Family Distribution">
      <data key="d0">Exponential Family Distribution</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Exponential family distribution is a group of probability distributions that can be expressed in a specific mathematical form, including logistic and Gaussian distributions.&lt;SEP&gt;The exponential family distribution is a class of probability distributions that includes the Gaussian distribution, as explained in the lecture.&lt;SEP&gt;The Exponential Family Distribution encompasses a set of probability distributions that share a common structure and can often be expressed in log-linear form, making them relevant in statistical modeling.&lt;SEP&gt;The Exponential Family Distribution is a class of probability distributions defined in terms of certain parameters and is mentioned in relation to the derivation of T of Y.&lt;SEP&gt;Exponential family distribution encompasses a set of probability distributions characterized by their mathematical properties, often used in statistical modeling.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1dcfa4fdc2012c4e3a3c336e39e4afec&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38d7cccd02d2282bbd339ef51ba43f85&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-486f08627d119b0879789e4cf88e8904&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-023cc775f8b1adeebc9c45d2e9f6fe90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-49f40563b7c8469bddeeb04d56b3cec7</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1767701765</data>
      <data key="d6" />
